hands_on_practices.solution:
We seek $\nabla^2f$ for 
$$f(x,y,z)=\ln\bigl(x^2+y^2\bigr)\,. $$
Let $r^2=x^2+y^2$. Then 
$$\frac{\partial f}{\partial x}
=\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\ln(r^2)
=\frac{1}{r^2}\,2x
=\frac{2x}{r^2},$$
and by the quotient rule
$$\frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial x^2}
=\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\Bigl(\frac{2x}{r^2}\Bigr)
=\frac{2\cdot r^2-2x\cdot 2x}{(r^2)^2}
=\frac{2(r^2-2x^2)}{r^4}
=\frac{2(y^2-x^2)}{r^4}\,. $$
Similarly,
$$\frac{\partial f}{\partial y}
=\frac{2y}{r^2},\qquad
\frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial y^2}
=\frac{2(r^2-2y^2)}{r^4}
=\frac{2(x^2-y^2)}{r^4}\,. $$
Since $f$ has no $z$-dependence, $\partial^2f/\partial z^2=0$. Hence
$$\nabla^2f
=\frac{\partial^2f}{\partial x^2}
+\frac{\partial^2f}{\partial y^2}
+\frac{\partial^2f}{\partial z^2}
=\frac{2(y^2-x^2)+2(x^2-y^2)}{r^4}+0
=0\,. $$
